### 2. `docs/design-anti-patterns.md` — amend AP-066

Find the existing `<a id="ap-066"></a>` section and replace it with:

```markdown
<a id="ap-066"></a>
## AP-066: Unconstrained Flex Compression Breaking Identity Text

**Status: ACTIVE**

**Trigger:** A nav logo or other identity-critical text sits as a flex item with
only `flex-shrink: 0` protecting it. Under viewport squeeze, the browser's flex
algorithm wraps the icon and text relative to each other (splitting across two
lines) even though the item technically doesn't shrink, because `white-space: nowrap`
was only applied to an inner text span rather than to the flex item container itself,
and no `min-width` floor was set.

**Why it's wrong:** `flex-shrink: 0` stops the item from consuming less *space* in
the flex row, but it does not stop the browser from reflowing the item's *internal*
layout to satisfy overflow. Without `min-width: max-content`, the browser is allowed
to use any sub-intrinsic width as a solution. Without `white-space: nowrap` on the
container element (not just on an inner span), the flex algorithm can still split
a mark+text pair across lines. The logo "Yilan Gao" wrapping to two lines is a
brand integrity failure — it communicates visual instability in the one element that
must always feel resolved (see `branding.md` §10).

**Correct alternative — the three-property lock:**
```scss
.logo {
  flex-shrink: 0;          // 1. item cannot shrink in the flex row
  min-width: max-content;  // 2. item's floor = its intrinsic rendered width
  white-space: nowrap;     // 3. internal layout cannot wrap (applied to the
                           //    flex item itself, not only to child spans)
}
```

The counterpart: the element beside the locked item must have `min-width: 0`
and `flex-shrink: 1` so all overflow resolves there instead:
```scss
.links {
  min-width: 0;
  flex-shrink: 1;
}
```

**Identity priority rule (branding.md §10):** Nav logos and core identity lines
are **compression-immune**. Adjacent soft content (taglines, role blurbs) are the
designated yield points and must be architected to absorb overflow via wrapping or
truncation. Never reverse this priority.

**See:** FB-146
```

