### 3. `docs/design/branding.md` — add §10 Nav Identity Priority

Append a new section at the end of the file (before any trailing matter):

```markdown
---

## 10. Nav Identity Priority — Compression-Immune Elements

### 10.1 The Rule

The nav logo ("Yilan Gao" wordmark + logomark) is a **compression-immune element**.
It must never wrap to two lines, shrink, or collapse under flex pressure at any
viewport width.

Adjacent soft content in the nav row — the role/tagline line — is the **designated
yield point**. It is explicitly allowed to wrap to two lines when the viewport is
squeezed. That is its correct behavior, not a failure.

| Element | Behavior under squeeze | Max lines |
|---------|----------------------|-----------|
| Logo wordmark (`Yilan Gao`) | **Never wraps. Never shrinks.** | 1 (always) |
| Logo mark (SVG icon) | Never shrinks | n/a |
| Role/tagline blurb | May wrap freely | 2 (clamped) |
| Nav links | May wrap or truncate | 1 preferred |

### 10.2 Implementation Contract

Every implementation of the nav **must** apply the three-property lock to the
logo element and the yield contract to the tagline (see AP-066):

```scss
// Logo — identity lock
.logo {
  flex-shrink: 0;
  min-width: max-content;
  white-space: nowrap;
}

// Tagline — designated yield point
.tagline {
  min-width: 0;
  flex-shrink: 1;
  -webkit-line-clamp: 2;
  line-clamp: 2;
  overflow: hidden;
}
```

### 10.3 Why

The logo is the only element on every page of the site that carries the designer's
name. If it wraps, it signals that the layout broke — not that it yielded gracefully.
A broken logo reads as inattention to craft, which directly contradicts the brand
position (§2). The tagline, by contrast, is supporting context. It compresses
gracefully. That trade-off is intentional.

### 10.4 Scope

This rule applies to all nav implementations on the main site:
`src/components/ui/Navigation/`. It does not apply to the Playground sidebar
or admin UI, where the logo treatment is different.

**See:** AP-066, FB-146
```

Also update `branding.md`'s `Last updated` line:

```markdown
> **Last updated:** 2026-04-27 (§10 added: Nav Identity Priority — compression-immune elements rule. Logo wordmark must never wrap; tagline is the designated yield point. Codified the three-property lock contract. FB-146.)
```

---

## Principle

**AP-066 — Identity Priority.** In any flex row that contains a brand identity element alongside soft supporting text, you must make an explicit architectural decision about which element yields. The logo is compression-immune (`flex-shrink: 0` + `min-width: max-content` + `white-space: nowrap` on the flex item itself). The tagline is the designated yield point (`min-width: 0` + `flex-shrink: 1` + `line-clamp`). `flex-shrink: 0` alone is not enough — it stops the item from *giving up space*, but doesn't tell the browser the item's *minimum width floor*. Without `min-width: max-content`, the browser is still free to use a narrower computed width and reflow the item's internal layout to fit it, which is exactly how the logo wraps even when its container is technically frozen.

